{
  "answer": "**In *San Hyan Mahajnana* (\"The Sacred Supreme Wisdom\"), a Medieval Indic work in Kawi, Kumāra asks the Lord Guru about mahājñāna (\"great knowledge\" or \"sacred supreme wisdom\").**[^1]\n\n**The text unfolds as a Shaivite *upadeśa* (teaching) using metaphors from yoga, cosmology, and daily life (e.g., sleeping/waking states, family as *prakṛti* and *guṇas*, chariot as body and senses, lotuses in heart/navel/throat, states of consciousness as *yugas*, *oṃkāra* as boat to liberation). It culminates in verses 84–87, defining mahājñāna as the great secret *jñāna*—eternally present across all states of being—realized by abandoning the manifest (*vyakta*, *prakṛti*) and unmanifest (*avyakta*, *puruṣa*), recognizing Shiva in the *ātma-liṅga* (Self-symbol) and the \"void within the void\" (*paramakaivalya*, supreme isolation):**[^2]\n\n> *In the great wisdom is the great secret, eternally in all states of being. The manifest and the unmanifest are to be abandoned; this is called the upadeśa. // 84*  \n> This *jñāna* is called the great wisdom, the culmination of the secret, eternally present in all states of being. The *vyakta* (the manifest) and the *avyakta* (the unmanifest), they must be abandoned. That is what is called the *upadeśa*.  \n> *In the great wisdom, the great teaching, [...] Shiva blossoms forth. For the awakening and grace of the disciple, this blessing we give to you. // 85*  \n> *In the great wisdom, the great tattva, here all doubts are finished. Shiva is situated in the ātma-liṅga, and in the void within the void. // 86*[^3]\n\n**This *jñānasandhi* (union of wisdom) is the brief essence yielding *mokṣa* (liberation), beyond syllables, form, or states.[^4]**\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1, paragraph p-573696](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-573696).\n\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/).\n\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1, paragraphs p-6436d4 to p-f7e6ce](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-6436d4).\n\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1, paragraphs p-ad1274 to p-0f7a95](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-ad1274).",
